\section{Reeb Flow and Orthogenetic Time}

The Reeb vector field \(R\) on a contact 3-manifold \((M^3,\alpha)\) is the unique vector field satisfying
\[
\alpha(R)=1,\qquad \iota_R d\alpha=0.
\]

It generates the characteristic foliation of the contact structure and defines a distinguished time direction transverse to the contact distribution \(\ker\alpha\).

In TOGT, the Reeb flow supplies perpetual orthogenetic time. Each integral curve of \(R\) is a closed or dense orbit on which the generative operator chain \(G = U \circ F \circ K \circ C\) acts iteratively. The flow preserves the contact volume form \(\alpha\wedge d\alpha\), ensuring that the geometric weight \(\eta^{-k}\) remains consistent across cycles.

Because \(\ker\alpha\) is maximally non-integrable, trajectories cannot remain planar; they must twist, accumulate curvature, and undergo fold events. This twisting is the geometric origin of the orthogenetic recurrence
\[
w(k+3)=w(k+2)+w(k+1)+w(k).
\]

In microtubules, the Reeb flow corresponds to longitudinal propagation of coherent dipole oscillations along the protofilament axis. The 13-protofilament lattice provides the contact 3-manifold on which this flow acts. General anesthetics collapse the geometric Born rule \(P_G(k)=|c_k|^2\eta^{-k}\), suspending orthogenetic time.

